Bias tetrahedrons emerge as vital components in the stability diagrams of quantum nanocrystals (QNCs), serving as crucial markers for quasiparticle physics studies. However, the complexities surrounding data quality and accessibility, coupled with the intricacies of the underlying physical processes, have obstructed the development of an automated and customizable analysis system. In response, we propose a feature extraction framework for bias tetrahedrons, rooted in unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision techniques. This methodology allows for the automatic identification and measurement of the physical attributes of these structures. By bypassing the reliance on human labeling and extensive training datasets, supervised learning methods can be circumvented. Moreover, this approach paves the way for the automation of pixel-wise shape and feature labeling. Notably, we exhibit that Pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection can be accomplished effectively, efficiently, and without the need for training data using this innovative approach.
